TY  - JOUR
AU  - G. Bali, Turan
AU  - Weigert, Florian
T1  - Hedge funds and the positive idiosyncratic volatility effect
PY  - 2024
Y1  - 2024/09/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfae022
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 28
IS  - 5
SP  - 1611
EP  - 1661
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - While it is established that idiosyncratic volatility is negatively priced in the cross-section of stock returns, the relation between idiosyncratic volatility and hedge fund returns is largely unexplored. We document that hedge funds with high idiosyncratic volatility earn higher future risk-adjusted returns of 6 percent p.a. than hedge funds with low idiosyncratic volatility. The outperformance arises because hedge funds trade high idiosyncratic volatility stocks wisely. They pick high volatility stocks when they are underpriced and short-sell high volatility stocks when they are overpriced. Our results support the notion that hedge funds’ idiosyncratic volatility is a measure of managerial skill.
Y2  - 4/28/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfae022
ER  - 




